objects.name: Adds other software
objects.description: This means downloading and installing other (unrelated) software, not for updating the current product, but for commercial/financial benefit.

objects.name: Alcohol
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that are related to the sale, promotion, or consumption of alcoholic beverages, including beer, wine, and hard liquors. This also includes sites that contain cocktail recipes and home brewing instructions.

Examples:    http://www.wine.com, http://www.smokers.com, http://www.finckcigarcompany.com

objects.name: Allows remote connect
objects.description: Allows (at least) part of the application to be controlled externally.

objects.name: Allows remote control
objects.description: Allow a remote user to connect to another user's machine to (near) full control over the PC as if they were sitting directly behind the PC.

objects.name: Anonymizer
objects.description:
An intermediary which prevents Web sites from seeing a user's Internet Protocol (IP) address.  Anonymizers are often used to circumvent company network acceptable use policies to potentially hide non-appropriate behavior, however in the home setting they may be used to provide additional layers of anonymity and protect privacy. 
 
Examples:    http://www.anonymizer.com, http://www.megaproxy.com, http://www.hidemyass.com

objects.name: Art / Culture
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that contain virtual art galleries, artist sites (includes sculpture and photograph), and other cultural topics like museums, ethnic customs, and country/regional customs. URLs that contain potentially offensive material will also be categorized with the appropriate category (e.g. Nudity). 
 
Examples:    http://www.polkmuseumofart.org, http://www.matsuoka-museum.jp

objects.name: BitTorrent protocol
objects.description: BitTorrent is a peer-to-peer file sharing (P2P) communications protocol. BitTorrent is a method of distributing large amounts of data widely without the original distributor incurring the entire costs of hardware, hosting, and bandwidth resources. Instead, when data is distributed using the BitTorrent protocol, each recipient supplies pieces of the data to newer recipients, reducing the cost and burden on any given individual source, providing redundancy against system problems, and reducing dependence on the original distributor.    The protocol is the brainchild of programmer Bram Cohen, who designed it in April 2001 and released a first implementation on 2 July 2001. It is now maintained by Cohen's company BitTorrent, Inc.    Usage of the protocol accounts for significant traffic on the Internet, but the precise amount has proven difficult to measure.    There are numerous compatible BitTorrent clients, written in a variety of programming languages, and running on a variety of computing platforms.

objects.name: Blogs / Personal Pages
objects.description: This category includes URLs where users post or edit content quickly and spontaneously. This includes, but is not limited to blogs and wikis. The category is meant to cover the risks associated with content that changes frequently according to user activity as it may range from harmless to offensive.

objects.name: Botnets
objects.description: Sites that use bots (zombies) including command-and-control sites.

objects.name: Browser Plugin
objects.description: Plug-ins are software programs that extend the capabilities of your Internet browser in a specific way. Not all browser plug-ins are harmful and some may be helpful. It is important to review the EULA of any browser plugin to make a determination of meeting enterprise standards or the standards for the home user.

objects.name: Browser Toolbar
objects.description: Browser Toolbar is a toolbar that resides within a browser's window. Web browsers provide support to browser toolbar development as a way to extend the browser's GUI and functionality.

objects.name: Business / Economy
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that provide business-related information. This includes corporate overviews, business planning, and strategies as well as information, services, or products that help other businesses plan, manage, or market their enterprises. 
 
Examples:    http://www.cat.com, www.cint.com, www.brandsoftheworld.com

objects.name: Business Applications
objects.description: Business application is one of the set of applications that are essential to running an enterprise.

objects.name: Child Abuse
objects.description: Sites that portray or discuss children in sexual or other abusive acts.

objects.name: Cloud Services
objects.description: Software as a Service that extends business application to the cloud ( public cloud) , either as free or payable service.

objects.name: Communication Standard
objects.description: Set of rules for communication between devices or apllications.

objects.name: Computers / Internet
objects.description:
This category is intended to cover websites related to computing software and hardware, as well as Internet and technology-related companies. This includes, but is not limited to vendors, product reviews, and deployment and maintenance of software and hardware. This also includes addons such as scripts, plugins, drivers, peripherals, and other equipment used in conjunction with computers and networks. 
 
Examples:    http://www.archive.org, http://www.verisign.com, http://www.limewire.com, http://www.w3schools.com

objects.name: Critical Risk
objects.description: Applications and Websites that may bypass security or hide identity.

objects.name: Cryptocurrency
objects.description: A cryptocurrency is a digital medium of exchange. Cryptocurrencies are specifications regarding the use of currency which seek to incorporate principles of cryptography to implement a distributed, decentralized and secure information economy.

objects.name: Download Manager
objects.description: A download manager is a software which is mainly used to download or upload files from or to the Internet for storage.

objects.name: Education
objects.description:
This category includes home pages of colleges, universities, and K-12 schools. 
 
Examples:    http://www.wikipedia.org, http://www.berkeley.edu, http://www.biology-online.org

objects.name: Email
objects.description:
Webmail is e-mail that is accessed via a web browser. 
 
Examples:    http://mail.live.com, http://mail.yahoo.com, http://www.gmail.com

objects.name: Encrypts communications
objects.description: Utilizes encrypted communications

objects.name: Entertainment
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that provide information about the entertainment industry. This includes, but is not limited to, cinema, theater, music, television, infotainment, entertainment industry gossip, sites about actors and musicians (including fan clubs), and horoscopes. 
 
Examples:    http://www.hollywood.com, http://disney.go.com, http://www.cinema-source.com/cinemasource/media.htm

objects.name: Facebook Business
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to business, such as finance.

objects.name: Facebook Education
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to education, such as philanthropy.

objects.name: Facebook Entertainment
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to entertainment, such as books, media, movies, music, etc.

objects.name: Facebook File Sharing
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to file sharing.

objects.name: Facebook Friends & Family
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to friends and family.

objects.name: Facebook Games
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to games, such as action & arcade games, etc.

objects.name: Facebook Lifestyle
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to lifestyle, such as arts, auto, dating, events, etc.

objects.name: Facebook Popular
objects.description: Facebook widgets with more than average 100,000 monthly users.

objects.name: Facebook Sports
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to sports.

objects.name: Facebook Utilities
objects.description: Facebook widgets related to utilities, such as communication utilities and news utilities.

objects.name: Facebook Widgets
objects.description: Facebook Applications that can be added to a users Facebook profile

objects.name: Fashion
objects.description: Sites concerning fashion. Includes product reviews, comparisons, and general consumer information.

objects.name: File Storage and Sharing
objects.description: This category includes file sharing applications and sites, for public or private sharing of data or space in a network. The data or space can be used, opened, changed, or deleted according to access privilege.

objects.name: Financial Services
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that provide financial information or access to online financial accounts. This includes, but is not limited to personal or business related banking, money management, tax consulting, mutual funds, credit cards, credit unions, insurance, or other financial publications and services.

Examples:    http://www.marketwatch.com, http://www.paypal.com, http://www.bankofamerica.com/index.cfm, http://www.etrade.com

objects.name: Friendster Widgets
objects.description: Widget applications you can add to your Friendster profile

objects.name: Gambling
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that allows users to place wagers or bets online or provide gambling-related software. This includes, but is not limited to online casinos, betting pools, sports betting, lotteries, and sites that are relevant to such activities. 
 
Examples:    http://www.silverdollar.com, http://www.desertdollar.eu, http://www.tnlottery.com

objects.name: Games
objects.description:
A game is an activity that provides entertainment or amusement. A game can be played solo or with a large group of people. Games can be played with or without structured rules depending on the game. Games generally challenge the mental and physical prowess of the person who is gaming.

Examples:    http://videogames.yahoo.com, http://www.megagames.com

objects.name: General
objects.description: Sites that do not clearly fall into other categories, for example, blank web pages.

objects.name: Gnutella protocol
objects.description: Gnutella is a file sharing network. Gnutella is the most popular file sharing network on the Internet with a market share of more than 40%. In June of 2005, Gnutella's population was 1.81 million computers.

objects.name: Google Plus Widgets
objects.description: Custom applications and widgets developed for Google Plus.

objects.name: Government / Military
objects.description:
This category includes URLs with content maintained by governmental organizations (e.g. government branches or agencies, police departments, fire departments, military branches or armed services) and supranational organizations such as the United Nations or the European Community. Sites maintained by non-governmental entities that provide information about government, military branches, or armed services are also included. 
 
Examples:    http://www.ca.gov, http://www.army.mil, http://www.gc.ca

objects.name: Greeting Cards
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that allow people to send and receive digital greeting cards via the Internet. These sites are used in the same way that people use conventional greeting cards (e.g. birthdays or holidays). They present a risk as sensitive or proprietary information may be leaked, or messages could contain objectionable information, malware, or harmful file attachments.

Examples:    http://www.americangreetings.com

objects.name: Hacking
objects.description: This category includes URLs that provide how-to information or otherwise enable fraud, crime, or computer-oriented malicious activity. This includes, but is not limited to sites that contain root kits, scripts or other software that can be used to compromise other computers, or otherwise illegally manipulate electronic devices.

objects.name: Hate / Racism
objects.description:
This category includes URLs that provide information that encourage oppression of a specific group of people. This includes, but is not limited to promoting (either explicitly or implicitly) an agenda against groups based on race, religion, nationality, gender, age, disability, or sexual orientation. This category also includes political parties that have a hate-based agenda. 
 
Examples:    http://www.kkkk.net
